# Project Title: Fish Schooling

## Project Members:
- Alex Garcia-Marin
- Ben Nguyen
- Yonash Petit
- Giovana Mitsunaga
- Michael Craig

## Description: 
This project is a sandbox in which the user simulates an ocean ecosystem. This simulation is meant to educate and engage the user by displaying steering behaviors in a fun and playful manner. Key behaviors are pursuit, obstacle avoidance, and flocking. Unique features include real-time editing of AI behaviors and dynamic ecosystem challenges.

Link to REPO: https://github.com/HuuBen5334/FishSchooling

## Prerequisites
1. Download Godot Engine 4.4.1 with .NET support from https://godotengine.org/download
   - **IMPORTANT**: Choose "Godot Engine - .NET" version (not the standard version)
   - Version 4.4.1 is required
   - Extract to a folder and note the path (e.g., `C:\Godot\Godot_v4.2-stable_mono_win64.exe`)

2. Install .NET SDK 6.0 or later from https://dotnet.microsoft.com/download
   - Required for C# script compilation

## Building from Source

### Method 1: From ZIP File (Recommended for Testers)
1. Extract the provided ZIP file
2. Open a command prompt/terminal
3. Navigate to the project folder:
```bash
   cd FishSchooling-main/fish-schooling
```
4. Build and run using Godot command line:
```bash
   # Replace the path with your actual Godot executable location
   "C:\Godot\Godot_v4.4.1-stable_mono_win64.exe" --export-release "Windows Desktop" ./FishSchooling.exe
```
   
   **Note**: If you haven't set up export templates yet, first run the project in editor:
```bash
   "C:\Godot\Godot_v4.2-stable_mono_win64.exe" --editor
```
   Then go to Project → Export → Add → Windows Desktop

   Ensure that the Export Path is set to `./FishSchooling.exe`

5. The executable will be created in the `fish-schooling` folder as `FishSchooling.exe`

### Method 2: From Git Repository
1. Clone the repository:
```bash
   git clone https://github.com/HuuBen5334/FishSchooling.git
   cd FishSchooling/fish-schooling
```
2. Follow steps 4-5 from Method 1 above
OR
Find the pre-built executable in the `fish-schooling` folder as `FishSchooling.exe`
